THE STORY IS ABOUT A LITTLE BOY WHO GREW UP IN THE 1940'S AND HE BELIEVED HE WAS RICH.
HIS PARENTS BROKE THE NEWS TO HIM THAT THEY WERE NOT A WEALTHY FAMILY, THEY WERE A POOR ONE.
LUCKILY THE FATHER GOT A LOB AS THE JANITOR FOR A LIBRARY AND HE TOOK HIS JOB VERY SERIOUSLY.
THE FATHER CLEANED UP THE LIBRARY WAXING EVERY SURFACE, EVEN THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES. HE TOOK A LOT OF PRIDE IN HIS WORK.
THE BOY WAS SOMEWHAT ASHAMED OF HIS FAMILY AND HE WANTED TO FIT IN AS A KID SO HE DID NOT INVITE ANYONE OVER.
THIS IS WHEN WE DISCOVER THAT HE LIVED IN THE LIBRARY.
THIS WAS ALSO WHEN HE REALIZED HOW GREAT HE HAD IT. HE LIVED IN THE LIBRARY AND HAD QUIET DAYS BUT FUN NIGHTS AFTER CLOSING TIME.
THE BOY WOULD WAKE UP AT 3AM AND READ BOOKS FROM THE LIBRARY.
THIS IS WHERE HE DEVELOPED HIS GRAND THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE.
THE BOY CAME FROM A FAMILY WHO HAD NO HIGH SCHOOL OR COLLEGE GRADUATES.
THE BOY WAS THE FIRST ONE TO COMPLETE BOTH HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE.
HE WENT ON TO BE A TEACHER. HE WAS A PROFESSOR AT A COLLEGE.
HE SHOWED HIS DAD HIS NAME ON THE DOOR WHEN HE BROUGHT HIM TO HIS PLACE OF WORK.
HIS DAD WAS VERY QUIET, BUT THE BOY (NOW GROWN INTO A MAN) COULD TELL THAT HE APPROVED.
HE KNEW THAT HIS FATHER WANTED HIM TO HAVE A BETTER LIFE THAN HE DID.
THE NARRATOR REFLECTS BACK ON HIS LIFE AND TALKS ABOUT HOW HE COULD NOT HAVE IMAGINED HIS LIFE IF HE DID NOT GROW UP IN THE LIBRARY.
HE REMEMBERS HIS UPBRINGING FONDLY AND IS PROUD OF IT.
A BOY GREW UP IN THE 1940'S THOUGHT HE WAS RICH.
HIS PARENTS HAD TO EXPLAIN TO HIM THAT THEY WERE NOT RICH, THEY WERE POOR.
THE DAD GOT LUCKY AND FOUND A JOB AS A CUSTODIAN IN A LIBRARY.
THE LIBRARY WAS DIRTY BUT THE DAD CLEANED AND WAVED EVERY SURFACE, INCLUDING THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
THE BOY WANTED TO FIT IN WITH HIS PEERS AT SCHOOL SO HE DID NOT TELL ANYONE WHERE HE LIVED AND NEVER INVITED ANYONE OVER.
AT FIRST HE WAS EMBARRASSED OF HIS LIFE AND THEN HE REALIZED HOW GREAT HE HAD IT.
HE HAD TO SPEND MANY HOURS QUIET DURING THE DAY, BUT AFTER CLOSING TIME HE WAS FREE TO SCREAM, YELL AND RUN IN THE LIBRARY.
THE LITTLE BOY WOULD STAY UP UNTIL 3AM READING BOOKS.
LIVING IN THE LIBRARY GAVE HIM A FIERCE THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE.
THE BOY'S FAMILY HAD NEVER GRADUATED FROM HIGH SCHOOL NOR COLLEGE.
THE BOY BECAME THE FIRST IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE FROM BOTH HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE.
HIS TIME READING BOOKS MOTIVATED HIM TO TEACH.
HE BECAME A PROFESSOR AT A COLLEGE.
ONE DAY THE MAIN CHARACTER (NO LONGER A BOY) SHOWED HIS FATHER HIS OFFICE AT THE UNIVERSITY.
HIS DAD WAS QUIET WHEN HE SAW HIS CHILD'S NAME ON THE DOOR BUT THE MAIN CHARACTER COULD TELL HE WAS HAPPY AND PROUD OF HIM.
HE KNEW HIS DAD WANTED WHAT WAS BEST FOR HIM AND TO HAVE A BETTER LIFE THAN HE DID.
THE NARRATOR CANNOT IMAGINE HIS LIFE GOING ANY DIFFERENTLY. LIVING IN A LIBRARY SHAPED THE KIND OF PERSON HE TURNED OUT TO BE.
